name: 08 - Lesson 2 - Main Text.mp3
format: mp3
duration: 02:00.529
id: 35ede59c-a247-4264-87a9-48fd686d75b6
clips:
  - id: cf4aacab-af53-4caa-a5e9-14881f5ae69f
    start: 00:06.22
    end: 00:16.62
    fields:
      transcription: |-
        人間の手は色々なことをするが、足のほうはあまり働かない。
        歩くことと走ることの他は大した仕事をしない。
      meaning: |-
        Although the human hand performs many functions, our feet hardly do any work at all. 
        Apart from walking and running, their workload is scant.
    tags:
      - iij02
  - id: c4e213ba-920f-4b99-9c46-ac20883e0288
    start: 00:17.18
    end: 00:29.7
    fields:
      transcription: |-
        特に足の裏は何も重要な働きはしていないように見える。
        ところが、足の裏の働きについて実験した結果、面白いことがわかったそうだ。
      meaning: |-2
         Whats more, the backs of our feet perform scarcely any major function. 
        Or so it had seemed, until a series of experiments on their activity came up with some interesting results. 
    tags:
      - iij02
  - id: fac39827-01e9-4ad8-b0ca-59924f624206
    start: 00:30.8
    end: 00:47.1
    fields:
      transcription: |-
        十二人の若い男女を二つの組に分ける。
        一定の時間、一方の組の人たちは、裸足になって竹を踏み続ける。
        もう一方の組は、高い椅子に腰掛けて、何もしないでいる。
      meaning: |-
        Twelve men and women, all of them young, were divided into two groups. 
        After taking off their shoes, the first group repeatedly stamped their feet on strips of bamboo for a specified period of time. 
        The second group simply sat motionless on a tall chair. 
    tags:
      - iij02
  - id: feecb4b5-2987-43b3-94c5-103cd32cffce
    start: 00:47.9
    end: 00:54.64
    fields:
      transcription: 椅子が高いので、足は床につかないから、足の裏には何の刺激もない。
      meaning: "The chair's height prevented their feet from touching the ground—and kept the backs of their feet from receiving any stimulus. "
    tags:
      - iij02
  - id: 833e3e3d-dbf8-44d5-b294-5f5eb33c9016
    start: 00:55.26
    end: 01:09.1
    fields:
      transcription: |-
        そのあと両方の組が同じゲームをする。
        テレビの画面に色の名前を表す漢字が出るが、その漢字の表す色と、漢字そのものの色は違っている。
      meaning: |-
        Later, the two groups took part in a game. 
        The names of colors were shown in kanji on a video monitor. The kanji were displayed in colors that differed from their meaning; 
    tags:
      - iij02
  - id: 56d57479-6c2d-4fce-9192-a8fb0c0f3532
    start: 01:09.46
    end: 01:18.28
    fields:
      transcription: |-
        例えば白い線で書いた「青」という字が出る。
        それを見て、いそいで「青」の札を探して高く上げる。
      meaning: |-
        For example, the character for "blue" was drawn with white lines. 
        After looking at the kanji for blue, the groups had to hastily search for a card displaying it, then raise this card high in the air. 
      notes: jí-ga déru
    tags:
      - iij02
  - id: 53df8e93-daaf-424e-a654-4f31abe161c9
    start: 01:18.78
    end: 01:28.48
    fields:
      transcription: 何回も続けると、疲れて間違いが多くなるが、二つの組のうち、竹を踏んだ人達のほうが成績がよかった。
      meaning: "After many attempts, the groups grew tired, and their mistakes multiplied. Yet the performance of the group that had stamped its feet on the bamboo was best. "
    tags:
      - iij02
  - id: a6941968-0cde-4337-80a3-e40535a19fa2
    start: 01:28.82
    end: 01:35.22
    fields:
      transcription: つまり足の裏を刺激すると、頭の働きがよくなることがわかったのである。
      meaning: "The experiment convinced its designers that, by stimulating the backs of our feet, we can upgrade the performance of our brains. "
    tags:
      - iij02
  - id: bea710d1-472b-4faf-aa60-ec3685db945b
    start: 01:36.16
    end: 01:51.72
    fields:
      transcription: |-
        むかしのある有名な人は、子供のころ家が貧乏で、一日中働いていたので、勉強する暇がなかった。
        そこで、背中に薪を背負って歩きながら、本を読んだそうである。
      meaning: "A famous person of old used to read while walking with a load of firewood on his back. As a child, his family was poor, and he had to work from dawn to dusk—leaving scarcely any time for study. "
    tags:
      - iij02
  - id: 091a8350-b944-4e64-8818-e4dd3fe0c523
    start: 01:52.2
    end: 02:00.0
    fields:
      transcription: 目のためには悪かったかもしれないが、頭の働きのためには、よい勉強法だったわけである。
      meaning: The child's study technique was undoubtedly bad for his eyesight. Yet for improving the performance of his mind, it was unexcelled.
    tags:
      - iij02
