name: 10 - Lesson 5 - KaiwaBun 2.mp3
format: mp3
duration: 01:11.837
id: a7f2f866-c933-40a6-94d8-d1a80dc0818c
subtitles:
  - id: 05e662a9-1db5-4e6c-918b-bb7fb9dd80f3
    type: External
    chunksMetadata:
      count: 28
      endCue: 3507.2
    name: 10 - Lesson 5 - KaiwaBun 2.srt
clips:
  - id: 3a68612d-00d6-4979-b6d4-842c633eea18
    start: 00:07.96
    end: 00:19.22
    fields:
      transcription: |-
        食事しようか。
        ええ。ここなんかどう？
        ここはだめ、地下だもの。
        じゃ、あのビルの中は？
        36階？だめだよ、そんな高いところ。
      meaning: |-
        Husband: Care for a bite to eat?
        Wife: Sure. What about this restaurant?
        Husband: No, not this restaurant. It's underground.
        Wife: Okay—so how about a restaurant in that building?
        Husband: The one on the 36th floor? No way—it's too high.
    tags:
      &a1
      - iij05
  - id: 4549612d-882a-4d49-8111-f316710bad8e
    start: 00:19.496
    end: 00:30.456
    fields:
      transcription: |-
        困るわねえ。高いところも嫌い、地下も嫌いだと、都心では安いレストランないわよ。
        僕は人間だよ。もぐらでもないし、鳥でもない。
      meaning: |-
        Wife: You're a real nuisance. You can't tolerate heights; you can't tolerate eating underground. We'll never be able to find a reasonable restaurant in the city center.
        Husband: Listen, I'm a human being. Not a mole or a bird.
    tags: *a1
  - id: 0ba80485-db5f-4207-9cfc-e9757b7f7c21
    start: 00:30.876
    end: 00:41.956
    fields:
      transcription: |-
        そんなこと言ったって、地下鉄に乗らないわけにはいかないじゃないの。
        地下鉄が限界だね。昨夜のテレビでやってたみたいに、地下の事務所で働くなんて、僕にはできないよ。
      meaning: |-
        Wife: If that's the case, how will you ever be able to ride the subway?
        Husband: Riding the subway is okay, but that's where I draw the line. I'd never be able to work in one of those underground offices we saw on TV last night.
    tags: *a1
  - id: fd7063de-346e-4be6-88ea-07289769e981
    start: 00:42.536
    end: 00:53.336
    fields:
      transcription: |-
        地下だと雨が降っても濡れないし、雪で道が滑ることもないし。
        それはそうだけど。
        事務所だけじゃなくて、住宅も地下になったらいいわね。
      meaning: |-
        Wife: Well, if it rains, you don't have to worry about getting wet if you're underground. And slippery streets aren't a concern if it snows.
        Husband: Maybe.
        Wife: And not only offices—wouldn't it be great if houses were underground, too?
    tags: *a1
  - id: 6fa6d5b9-c24a-4ae5-8165-44cd5180572d
    start: 00:53.736
    end: 01:01.716
    fields:
      transcription: |-
        朝、傘を持って行こうか どうしようか悩むこともないし。
        僕は嫌だよ。
        地上にいて毎日傘を持って歩く方がいい。
      meaning: |-
        Wife: That would put an end to worrying about whether to leave home with an umbrella in the morning.
        Husband: Well, I feel differently. I'd prefer to live aboveground, even if it means having to lug along an umbrella everyday.
    tags: *a1
  - id: f9c327c3-ad9d-4cd7-b3a7-2b94700905cb
    start: 01:02.66
    end: 01:10.22
    fields:
      transcription: |-
        ここにしましょう。１階よ。
        高そうだなあ。
        仕方がないでしょ、入りましょう。
      meaning: |-
        Wife: Hey, why don't we eat here. It's on the first floor.
        Husband: It looks kind of expensive.
        Wife: Let's go in anyway. We don't have much of a choice.
    tags: *a1
